      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "PR #442, 'legacy-framework-deprecation', is indeed a significant overhaul, and I appreciate the need for clarity. The deprecation of the autonomous agent runtime is a major shift, as it replaces the self-contained agents with stateless lambda functions. This transition is designed to improve scalability and reduce overhead, but it requires careful examination of the core logic that previously relied on the agents' statefulness.\n\nThe switch to stateless lambda functions means that any logic that depended on maintaining state across invocations will need to be restructured. This includes session management, persistent data storage, and any form of stateful computation. The lambda functions will now need to interact with external services or databases to retrieve and store state, which could introduce latency and complexity.\n\nTo ensure a smooth transition and avoid breaking core logic, a detailed audit of all components interacting with the autonomous agents is necessary. This includes reviewing API endpoints, data flow diagrams, and any custom middleware that facilitated state management. Additionally, the impact on existing workflows and user interactions must be assessed to identify any potential disruptions.\n\nA comprehensive testing strategy, including unit, integration, and end-to-end tests, will be crucial to validate the new architecture. Performance benchmarks should be established to compare the old and new systems,",
